---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base title="Coherence — WTF" description="The 5-minute version for someone who's never heard of Coherence. Why it exists, what it does, and how it works.">
  <article class="container guide">
    <header class="guide-header">
      <a href="/" class="back-link">&larr; Home</a>
      <p class="section-label">WTF</p>
      <h1>Coherence</h1>
      <p class="guide-subtitle">
        The 5-minute version for someone who's never heard of it.
      </p>
    </header>

    <nav class="toc">
      <p class="toc-title">On this page</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#why">Why</a></li>
        <li><a href="#what">What</a></li>
        <li><a href="#when">When</a></li>
        <li><a href="#who">Who</a></li>
        <li><a href="#how">How</a></li>
      </ul>
    </nav>

    <div class="prose">

      <!-- ============================================ -->
      <section id="why" class="guide-section">
        <h2>Why: <span class="h2-sub">AI removed the bottleneck, and revealed a harder one</span></h2>
        <p>
          For most of software engineering's history, the bottleneck was writing code. Not thinking about it &mdash; <em>writing</em> it. The mechanical act of translating intention into syntax, across files, tested, debugged, committed. That's where the clock burned.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI-assisted development largely removes that bottleneck. What took an afternoon now takes minutes. You describe what you want, an agent produces it, you review and refine. The throughput increase isn't marginal &mdash; it's an order of magnitude.
        </p>
        <p>
          But removing one bottleneck reveals the next. And the constraint that emerges when code flows freely is <em>coherence</em>: keeping a codebase internally consistent as it changes faster than any human can manually track. Every generated file is syntactically correct and locally sensible. But does it follow the conventions the rest of the codebase established? Does it know about the routing prefix every endpoint requires? Does it understand why the database queries need tenant filters?
        </p>
        <p>
          This is entropy at velocity. The code compiles. The tests pass. And the problem doesn't surface until a customer reports they're seeing someone else's data. You need architecture encoded into the generation loop itself, not enforced after the fact.
        </p>
        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Want the full story?</strong> Read <a href="/blog/entropy-at-velocity">Entropy at Velocity</a> &mdash; the deep version of this argument with examples, failure modes, and the four-layer solution in detail.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============================================ -->
      <section id="what" class="guide-section">
        <h2>What: <span class="h2-sub">Active guardrails inside the generation loop</span></h2>
        <p>
          Coherence is a system of SPEC documents, agents, a nudge hook, and a single auto-detecting skill that encode your project's architectural constraints into the <a href="https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Claude Code</a> development loop. Instead of writing rules in a document and hoping the AI follows them, you make the rules <em>active</em> &mdash; SPEC docs define what's correct, agents detect drift, and a hook nudges you when it's time to check.
        </p>

        <h3>How it compares</h3>
        <div class="comparison-table">
          <div class="comparison-row comparison-header">
            <div class="comparison-approach">Approach</div>
            <div class="comparison-detail">What it does</div>
            <div class="comparison-limit">Where it falls short</div>
          </div>
          <div class="comparison-row">
            <div class="comparison-approach"><code>CLAUDE.md</code> alone</div>
            <div class="comparison-detail">Passive instructions the agent reads at session start</div>
            <div class="comparison-limit">Agent can ignore, forget, or misinterpret mid-session</div>
          </div>
          <div class="comparison-row">
            <div class="comparison-approach">Linters (ESLint, etc.)</div>
            <div class="comparison-detail">Catch syntax-level patterns</div>
            <div class="comparison-limit">Can't express architectural intent like "don't cross this boundary"</div>
          </div>
          <div class="comparison-row">
            <div class="comparison-approach">Code review</div>
            <div class="comparison-detail">Human catches violations</div>
            <div class="comparison-limit">Happens <em>after</em> the work is done &mdash; rework is expensive</div>
          </div>
          <div class="comparison-row comparison-row-highlight">
            <div class="comparison-approach"><strong>Coherence</strong></div>
            <div class="comparison-detail">SPEC-based drift detection plus nudge reminders during development</div>
            <div class="comparison-limit">Catches drift before it compounds</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>The four layers</h3>
        <div class="layers-table">
          <div class="layer-row layer-header">
            <div class="layer-name">Layer</div>
            <div class="layer-purpose">Purpose</div>
            <div class="layer-when">When it runs</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-row">
            <div class="layer-name"><strong>Hooks</strong></div>
            <div class="layer-purpose">Nudge when edits accumulate without a drift check</div>
            <div class="layer-when">PostToolUse on edits and writes</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-row">
            <div class="layer-name"><strong>Agents</strong></div>
            <div class="layer-purpose">Review code and detect drift (read-only)</div>
            <div class="layer-when">Invoked by <code>/coherence</code> or directly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-row">
            <div class="layer-name"><strong>SPEC docs</strong></div>
            <div class="layer-purpose">Define "correct" via falsifiable claims</div>
            <div class="layer-when">Referenced by agents during checks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="layer-row">
            <div class="layer-name"><strong>Skills</strong></div>
            <div class="layer-purpose">Single auto-detecting entry point for drift, plans, and fixes</div>
            <div class="layer-when">User-invoked (<code>/coherence</code>)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============================================ -->
      <section id="when" class="guide-section">
        <h2>When: <span class="h2-sub">Setup once, nudged during development, drift-checked on demand</span></h2>
        <p>
          Coherence works during development with Claude Code. Different parts activate at different times:
        </p>

        <div class="lifecycle">
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-once">once</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Install &amp; setup</strong>
              <p>Install the plugin and run <code>/coherence</code>. It auto-detects a fresh project and scaffolds everything &mdash; CLAUDE.md, SPEC docs, agents, and a nudge hook.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-auto">automatic</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Nudge hook tracks edits</strong>
              <p>No action needed. The <code>spec-drift-nudge</code> hook counts edits and elapsed time. After 50 edits or 7 days, it nudges you to run <code>/coherence</code>. Non-blocking, non-intrusive.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-demand">on demand</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Run /coherence when you're ready</strong>
              <p>Run <code>/coherence</code> to detect drift against your SPECs. Run <code>/coherence plan</code> to review a plan against constraints. Use <code>/coherence fix</code> to auto-apply corrections.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Lifecycle summary:</strong> Install &rarr; Setup &rarr; Develop (hooks active) &rarr; Periodically check drift.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ============================================ -->
      <section id="who" class="guide-section">
        <h2>Who: <span class="h2-sub">Anyone with conventions worth protecting</span></h2>
        <p>
          You're probably not just a coder. You might be an architect trying to keep a growing system consistent, a marketer protecting brand voice, or a writer enforcing terminology across a documentation set. Coherence works for any project with architectural conventions worth protecting &mdash; web apps, APIs, CLIs, infrastructure, content, and more.
        </p>
        <p>
          The single <code>/coherence</code> skill auto-detects your stack and generates SPEC documents and CLAUDE.md content tailored to what you're building. The same hook and agents work across all project types &mdash; what changes is the content of your SPECs, not the tooling.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- ============================================ -->
      <section id="how" class="guide-section">
        <h2>How: <span class="h2-sub">Two commands and a wizard versus doing it all by hand</span></h2>

        <h3>Without Coherence</h3>
        <div class="contrast-card contrast-without">
          <ul>
            <li>Write a <code>CLAUDE.md</code> and hope Claude reads it</li>
            <li>Manually review every generated file for convention violations</li>
            <li>Notice drift weeks later when something breaks in production</li>
            <li>Keep specs updated by memory &mdash; forget, and they rot</li>
            <li>Spend more time policing conventions than building features</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>With Coherence</h3>
        <div class="contrast-card contrast-with">
          <ul>
            <li>2 commands to install, 1 command to set up</li>
            <li>A nudge hook reminds you when it's time to check for drift</li>
            <li>Agents detect spec drift on demand</li>
            <li>SPEC docs make falsifiable claims &mdash; verifiable, not aspirational</li>
            <li>Architecture participates in code generation, not just code review</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Scenarios</h3>
        <p>What does using Coherence actually look like day-to-day? Here are the common starting points.</p>

        <div class="lifecycle">
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">fresh start</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>New blank repo</strong>
              <p>You're starting from scratch. Run <code>/coherence</code> &mdash; it detects an empty project, scaffolds everything (CLAUDE.md, SPEC docs, agents, nudge hook), and you're ready to go.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">existing code</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Cloned repo (someone else's code)</strong>
              <p>You've <code>git clone</code>'d a project and want guardrails. Run <code>/coherence</code> &mdash; it scans the existing structure and scaffolds SPEC docs matched to what's there. Create SPECs when you understand the architecture, then run <code>/coherence</code> again to verify them.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">your project</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Your own existing repo</strong>
              <p>You've been building this for a while. Run <code>/coherence</code> &mdash; it detects your stack and generates SPECs. If you already have a <code>.claude/</code> directory, it asks whether to overwrite, merge, or abort.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">feature branch</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Feature branch workflow</strong>
              <p>Create a branch, build your feature with the nudge hook tracking your progress. Before merging, run <code>/coherence</code> to check drift and <code>/coherence plan</code> to validate your approach. Merge with confidence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">hotfix</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Quick fix straight to master</strong>
              <p>The nudge hook still runs on every edit &mdash; even a quick patch to master is tracked. No ceremony needed. Run <code>/coherence</code> after if you want extra assurance.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">worktree</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Working in a worktree</strong>
              <p>Worktrees (via Claude Code's <code>/worktree</code> or <code>git worktree</code>) give you an isolated copy of the repo. Your <code>.claude/</code> directory is part of the repo, so hooks and settings travel with the worktree automatically. <code>/coherence</code> works the same in a worktree as in the main tree.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="lifecycle-step">
            <div class="lifecycle-badge lifecycle-scenario">cleanup</div>
            <div class="lifecycle-detail">
              <strong>Removing Coherence from a repo</strong>
              <p>Use Claude Code's built-in plugin management: <code>/plugin uninstall coherence</code> removes the plugin. To clean up generated files (<code>.claude/hooks/</code>, agents, skills, <code>settings.local.json</code>), delete them directly or ask Claude to help.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Get started in 30 seconds</h3>
        <div class="terminal">
          <div class="terminal-header">
            <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
            <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
            <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
            <span class="terminal-title">Claude Code</span>
          </div>
          <div class="terminal-body">
            <span class="comment"># Add the marketplace</span><br />
            <span class="prompt">&gt;</span> /plugin marketplace add viewyonder/coherence<br />
            <br />
            <span class="comment"># Install the plugin (accept the default "user" scope)</span><br />
            <span class="prompt">&gt;</span> /plugin install coherence<br />
            <br />
            <span class="comment"># Run in any project — auto-detects and scaffolds</span><br />
            <span class="prompt">&gt;</span> /coherence
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <strong>Scope matters.</strong>
          When prompted for a scope, choose <code>user</code> (the default).
          Coherence is a multi-repo tool &mdash; you install the plugin once at user scope, then run <code>/coherence</code> in each project to generate per-project guardrails.
          Installing with <code>local</code> scope locks the plugin to a single project. You'll get an "already installed" error when you try to add it to a second repo.
        </div>

        <div class="cta-block">
          <a href="/getting-started" class="cta-link">Read the full Getting Started guide &rarr;</a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .guide {
    padding-top: 7rem;
    padding-bottom: 4rem;
  }

  .guide-header {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .guide-subtitle {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    max-width: 50ch;
  }

  /* Table of contents */
  .toc {
    background: var(--bg-mid);
    border: 1px solid var(--bg-surface);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.5rem 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
    max-width: 500px;
  }

  .toc-title {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .toc ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .toc li {
    margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }

  .toc a {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .toc a:hover {
    color: var(--cyan);
    opacity: 1;
  }

  /* Sections */
  .guide-section {
    padding: 0;
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .guide-section h2 {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .h2-sub {
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-size: 0.85em;
  }

  .guide-section h3 {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .guide-section p {
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  /* Callout */
  .callout {
    background: var(--bg-mid);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--cyan);
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius) var(--radius) 0;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .callout strong {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .callout-warn {
    border-left-color: var(--amber, #ffa600);
  }

  /* Comparison table */
  .comparison-table {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--bg-surface);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .comparison-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr 1fr;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--bg-surface);
  }

  .comparison-row:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .comparison-header {
    background: var(--bg-surface);
  }

  .comparison-header div {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .comparison-row div {
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .comparison-approach {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .comparison-row-highlight {
    background: rgba(0, 255, 240, 0.05);
  }

  .comparison-row-highlight .comparison-limit {
    color: var(--green) !important;
  }

  /* Layers table */
  .layers-table {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
    border: 1px solid var(--bg-surface);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .layer-row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 120px 1fr 1fr;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--bg-surface);
  }

  .layer-row:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .layer-header {
    background: var(--bg-surface);
  }

  .layer-header div {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .layer-row div {
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .layer-name {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
  }

  /* Lifecycle */
  .lifecycle {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .lifecycle-step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    background: var(--bg-mid);
    border: 1px solid var(--bg-surface);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
  }

  .lifecycle-badge {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    padding: 0.25em 0.7em;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .lifecycle-once {
    background: rgba(136, 136, 255, 0.12);
    color: #88f;
    border: 1px solid rgba(136, 136, 255, 0.3);
  }

  .lifecycle-auto {
    background: rgba(0, 255, 136, 0.12);
